def missing_values(df: pandas.DataFrame) -> pandas.DataFrame:
    nan_values_count = df.isna().sum()
    nan_values_percent = nan_values_count / len(df)
    nan_values = pandas.concat([nan_values_count, nan_values_percent], axis=1, keys=['Missing', 'Percent'])
    return nan_values.sort_values(by='Missing', ascending=False)

2.1. Missing Values¶

There are many ways to handle missing values.

  • Dropping:
    • Dropping Columns:
      In this method we remove any column that has missing values in it.
      This is usually not wanted because we potentially losing a lot of data.
      This method should only be considered on columns that have too many missing values; and in fact, its actually the better thing to do in such cases because there is not much data to fill it with good precision.
    • Dropping Rows:
      Works similarly to dropping columns.
      If we remove all rows that have missing values, if a column is all missing, then all of the rows will be gone.
      This method should also only be considered on rows that have most of their properties missing.
  • Imputation:
    Imputation is the process of replacing missing values with a substitution.
    • Filling with Mean:
      Using the average to fill missing values is simple to do and the mean is a good representative of the data as a whole.
      But sometimes it may not make sense and be impossible to use for a column.
    • Filling with Median:
      The outlier data can affect the mean negatively.
      In such cases, it may be better to use the median which is not affected by outliers.
    • Filling with Mode:
      Mean and median do not work with categorical data.
      Using the mode can be a alternative for such data.
    • Random Fill:
      In this method we fill using random values, mostly in the range of the column's minimum and maximum data, or between the categories.
    • Predicting:
      A more advanced method is to have a way of predicting what the missing value should be based on the other properties of the row.

2.3. Normalization and Standardization¶

Normalizing makes all of the data fit in the range of 0 to 1. (divide by data count)
Standardizing (Z-Score) changes the data so that the standard deviation is 1 and the mean is 0. (subtract mean and divide by standard deviation)

These methods are used to scale the data.
Scaling is changing the range of the values without changing the shape of the distribution.
This is important for methods that rely on data distance such as KNN.

Standardization assumes a Gaussian distribution in our data and works better if that is the case.
Normalization is highly affected by outliers and is not a good choice if our data has outliers.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler


class DataScaler:
    def __init__(self, dataframe: pandas.DataFrame):
        self.dataframe = dataframe
        self.numeric_cols = dataframe.select_dtypes(include='number')
        self.scaler_std = StandardScaler()
        self.scaler_norm = MinMaxScaler()

    def standard(self, exclude_cols: list = []):
        self.dataframe[self.numeric_cols.columns] = self.scaler_std.fit_transform(self.numeric_cols)
        self.dataframe[exclude_cols] = self.numeric_cols[exclude_cols]

    def normal(self, exclude_cols: list = []):
        self.dataframe[self.numeric_cols.columns] = self.scaler_norm.fit_transform(self.numeric_cols)
        self.dataframe[exclude_cols] = self.numeric_cols[exclude_cols]


scaler = DataScaler(diabetes_df)
scaler.normal(exclude_cols=['Outcome'])

2.4. Categorical Values¶

There are many ways to handle categorical columns:

  • Label Encoding:
    This is substituting each possible value of a categorical feature with a corresponding number.
    While label encoding is very simple, it is not always ideal because the numbers do not mean anything and can cause issues if used for calculating distance.
    This method should not be used for non-ordinal features but works fine with ordinal features.
  • One-Hot Encoding:
    In this method, an additional feature is added for each categorical value and is marked 0 or 1.
    While this encoding is more proper, it adds a lot of new binary features which use more memory and can slow the dataset down.
  • Target Encoding:
    This is the process of replacing a categorical value with the mean of a target variable.
    To do this, the data is grouped by each categorical value, and the average of a chosen target variable is calculated for that group.
    If the target is numerical, the categorical values are replaced with their corresponding average of the target.
    If the target is categorical, the values are replaced with their corresponding probability of the target.
  • Frequency Encoding:
    In this method, each categorical value is replaced with its frequency in the column.
  • Binary Encoding:
    An ordinal encoding (such as label encoding) is applied, then the integers are converted to their binary form.
    Now the digits from the binary representation are split to separate columns.
    The result looks similar to one-hot encoding but uses less space.
In [ ]:
import category_encoders as cat_enc


class CategoricalEncoder:
    def __init__(self, dataframe: pandas.DataFrame):
        self.dataframe = dataframe
        self.cat_cols = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['category', 'object'])
        self.label_enc = cat_enc.OrdinalEncoder(cols=self.cat_cols.columns)
        self.onehot_enc = cat_enc.OneHotEncoder(cols=self.cat_cols.columns, use_cat_names=True)
        self.target_enc = cat_enc.TargetEncoder(cols=self.cat_cols.columns, min_samples_leaf=2, smoothing=1.1)
        self.freq_enc = cat_enc.CountEncoder(cols=self.cat_cols.columns)
        self.binary_enc = cat_enc.BinaryEncoder(cols=self.cat_cols.columns)

    def label(self):
        self.dataframe[self.cat_cols.columns] = self.label_enc.fit_transform(self.cat_cols)

    def onehot(self):
        self.dataframe[self.cat_cols.columns] = self.onehot_enc.fit_transform(self.cat_cols)

    def target(self, target: str):
        self.dataframe[self.cat_cols.columns] = self.target_enc.fit_transform(self.cat_cols, self.dataframe[target])

    def freq(self):
        self.dataframe[self.cat_cols.columns] = self.freq_enc.fit_transform(self.cat_cols)

    def binary(self):
        self.dataframe[self.cat_cols.columns] = self.binary_enc.fit_transform(self.cat_cols)


encoder = CategoricalEncoder(diabetes_df)

2.6. Test and Train Data¶

To test a model, we have to first feed and train it with some data, then use some other data to test and see how much it guesses them correctly.

If we have one answer-labeled dataset, we have to split it into two parts: the test and the train data.
Usually about 3/4 of the data is used for training and the rest is used for testing.
The common splitting method is to select randomly. Basically to first shuffle the data and then select the first fourth for testing and the rest for training.

Another model validation method is called cross-validation which groups the data into k parts, and chooses one of them at each iteration and uses it as the test data, while using the rest as training data.
K-fold cross-validation is simply splitting into k parts.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from dataclasses import dataclass

class DataSplitter:
    def __init__(self, dataframe: pandas.DataFrame, outcome: str, train_percent: float = 0.7):
        self.ddata = dataframe.drop(columns=[outcome])
        self.odata = dataframe[outcome]
        self._split(train_percent)

    def _split(self, train_percent: float):
        split_data = train_test_split(self.ddata, self.odata, train_size=train_percent, random_state=1)
        train_feat, test_feat, train_out, test_out = split_data
        self.dtrain = train_feat
        self.dtest = test_feat
        self.otrain = train_out
        self.otest = test_out

splitter = DataSplitter(diabetes_df, 'Outcome')

2.7. Validation Data¶

Validation is another data category that is sometimes used.
Here, the main dataset is split into three parts: train, validation, and test.
Their division percentage is about 70-15-15 percent of the data respectively.

The validation data is used to test the trained model before using the testing data.
During this step, the classifier hyperparameters are adjusted.

In [ ]:
class DtreeClassifier:
    def __init__(self, split: DataSplitter):
        self.split = split
        self._init()

    def _init(self):
        self.dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=8, min_samples_split=8,
                                            min_samples_leaf=2, random_state=1)
        self.dtree.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        self.dtree_predict = self.dtree.predict(self.split.dtest)

    def accuracy(self) -> float:
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otest, self.dtree_predict)

    def accuracy_train(self) -> float:
        train_predict = self.dtree.predict(self.split.dtrain)
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otrain, train_predict)

    def confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix_dtree = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.split.otest, self.dtree_predict)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix_dtree)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('Decision Tree Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()

    def grid_search(self) -> tuple[float, GridSearchCV]:
        search_params = {
            'criterion': ['entropy'],
            'max_depth': range(4, 12),
            'min_samples_split': range(2, 12),
            'min_samples_leaf': range(1, 10),
            'random_state': [1]
        }
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.dtree, search_params, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=2)
        grid.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        test_score = grid.score(self.split.dtest, self.split.otest)
        return test_score, grid

class KnearClassifier:
    def __init__(self, split: DataSplitter, n_neighbors: int = 11):
        self.split = split
        self.n_neighbors = n_neighbors
        self._init()

    def _init(self):
        self.knear = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=self.n_neighbors)
        self.knear.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        self.knear_predict = self.knear.predict(self.split.dtest)

    def accuracy(self) -> float:
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otest, self.knear_predict)

    def accuracy_train(self) -> float:
        train_predict = self.knear.predict(self.split.dtrain)
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otrain, train_predict)

    def confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix_knear = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.split.otest, self.knear_predict)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix_knear)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('K Nearest Neighbors Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()

    def grid_search(self) -> tuple[float, GridSearchCV]:
        search_params = {
            'n_neighbors': range(1, 20)
        }
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.knear, search_params, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=2)
        grid.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        test_score = grid.score(self.split.dtest, self.split.otest)
        return test_score, grid

3.1. Confusion Matrix¶

In a confusion matrix, we have the following structure:

Predicted Results
Value 0 1
Actual 0 TN FP
Results 1 FN TP
  • TN (True Negative): The actual result is false, and the model correctly predicted it as false.
  • FP (False Positive): The actual result is false, but the model wrongly predicted it as true.
  • FN (False Negative): The actual result is true, but the model wrongly predicted it as false.
  • TP (True Positive): The actual result is true, and the model correctly predicted it as true.

Some of the metrics used to assess the prediction results are as follow:

$$ Accuracy = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN} $$$$ Precision = \frac{TP}{TP + FP},\, Recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN} $$

Here we focus on accuracy and show that it matches with the results of 3.0:

  • Decision Tree: $ \frac{60 + 125}{60 + 125 + 21 + 25} = 0.80086 \longrightarrow 80.086\% $
  • K Nearest Neighbors: $ \frac{49 + 132}{49 + 132 + 14 + 36} = 0.78355 \longrightarrow 78.355\% $
  • Logistic Regression: $ \frac{45 + 134}{45 + 134 + 12 + 40} = 0.77489 \longrightarrow 77.489\% $

3.2. GridSearchCV¶

GridSearchCV searches all possibilities within the given search parameters and chooses the one which yields the highest results.
The GridSearch is fit on the training data, and evaluates on itself.
Basically, it splits the training data to use a part of it for testing; similar idea to validation data explained in 2.7.

The classifiers' grid_search method scores the grid search results on the testing data and returns it along with the chosen parameters.

3.3. Underfitting and Overfitting¶

First, we need to explain bias and variance:

  • Bias:
    Bias is how precise we are at training the subtleties of the training data.
    The more precise we are, the lower the bias.
    This means that we are taking every feature and perhaps the noisy data into account.
    The lower the bias, the lower our detection error is on the training data.
    This is not necessarily good because we train on the wrong and noisy data which will lower the generalization of the classifier.
  • Variance:
    Variance is a measure of how good the classifier is on unseen data.
    The better it is on testing data, the lower the variance.
    This means that the classifier is generalized enough and can detect the testing data correctly.

As much as we want low bias and variance at once, that is not usually the case because once we lower one, the other one increases.
This is called the bias-variance tradeoff.

Now to explain over and underfitting:

  • Overfitting:
    This happens when the variance is high and the bias is low.
    This means that the model works well on the training data but not on the testing data.
  • Underfitting:
    This happens when the bias is high and the variance is low.
    This means that the model does not work well even on the training data.
    The variance is low which means its very generalized. But this does not necessarily mean that it works well on testing data.

Now we will check if such cases have happened in our classifiers:

In [ ]:

Part 4. Ensemble Learning¶

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier


class RandForestClassifier:
    def __init__(self, split: DataSplitter, n_estimators: int = 100, max_depth: int = 8):
        self.split = split
        self.n_estimators = n_estimators
        self.max_depth = max_depth
        self._init()

    def _init(self):
        self.randf = RandomForestClassifier(criterion='entropy',
                                            max_depth=self.max_depth,
                                            n_estimators=self.n_estimators,
                                            random_state=1)
        self.randf.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        self.randf_predict = self.randf.predict(self.split.dtest)

    def accuracy(self) -> float:
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otest, self.randf_predict)

    def accuracy_train(self) -> float:
        train_predict = self.randf.predict(self.split.dtrain)
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.split.otrain, train_predict)

    def confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix_randf = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.split.otest, self.randf_predict)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix_randf)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('Random Forest Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()

    def grid_search(self) -> tuple[float, GridSearchCV]:
        search_params = {
            'n_estimators': range(70, 230, 30),
            'criterion': ['entropy'],
            'max_depth': range(4, 10),
            'random_state': [1]
        }
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.randf, search_params, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=2)
        grid.fit(self.split.dtrain, self.split.otrain)
        test_score = grid.score(self.split.dtest, self.split.otest)
        return test_score, grid

4.1. Hyperparameters¶

Some of the hyperparameters for the random forest classifier include:

  • n_estimators: This is the number of decision trees.
  • criterion: The means of assessing the quality of a split. 'entropy' is the information gain method.
  • max_depth: This is the maximum depth of the decision trees.

Most of the DecisionTreeClassifier hyperparameters can also be applied here.

We will now plot 2 of the hyperparameters: n_estimators and max_depth.

In [ ]:
def n_estimators_effects():
    n_estimators = range(1, 200, 10)
    res = []
    for est_count in n_estimators:
        randf = RandForestClassifier(splitter, n_estimators=est_count)
        res.append(randf.accuracy())

    plt.plot(n_estimators, res)
    plt.xlabel('n_estimators')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')


def max_depth_effects():
    max_depths = range(1, 20)
    res = []
    for depth in max_depths:
        randf = RandForestClassifier(splitter, max_depth=depth)
        res.append(randf.accuracy())

    plt.plot(max_depths, res)
    plt.xlabel('max_depth')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.suptitle('Hyperparameter Effects on Accuracy')
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
n_estimators_effects()
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
max_depth_effects()

Increasing the number of trees help cover more feature combinations for the trees in the forest. Since we get the majority vote of the tree results, the more trees we have, the better our result can be.
Increasing the max depth of each tree can also help because we get closer to the low biased result.

4.2. Versus Decision Tree¶

Bias and variance are explained in 3.3.

A decision tree will usually have low bias and is sensitive to the subtle details of the training data. This lowers the generalization power and increases variance.
A random forest is a form of bagging. It is an ensemble of decision trees that takes majority vote between trees of different features.
This is designed to correct decision trees' overfitting problems.

In [ ]:
from mlxtend.evaluate import bias_variance_decomp


_, dtree_bias, dtree_var = bias_variance_decomp(dtree_clf.dtree,
                                                splitter.dtrain.values, splitter.otrain.values,
                                                splitter.dtest.values, splitter.otest.values,
                                                loss='mse', random_seed=1)
_, randf_bias, randf_var = bias_variance_decomp(randf_clf.randf,
                                                splitter.dtrain.values, splitter.otrain.values,
                                                splitter.dtest.values, splitter.otest.values,
                                                loss='mse', random_seed=1)

print(f'Decision Tree Bias:     {dtree_bias:.3f}')
print(f'Decision Tree Variance: {dtree_var:.3f}')
print(f'Random Forest Bias:     {randf_bias:.3f}')
print(f'Random Forest Variance: {randf_var:.3f}')

Decision Tree Bias:     0.156
Decision Tree Variance: 0.130
Random Forest Bias:     0.182
Random Forest Variance: 0.059

The above calculations show how decision tree has a lower bias and is more overfitted, while random forest has lower variance and is more generalized.
